&quot;The history of liberty is a history of limitation of government power, not the increase of it.&quot;  <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>Woodrow Wilson</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
<br>
&quot;Liberty has never come from the government. Liberty has always come from the subjects of it. The history of liberty is a history of resistance.&quot;  <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>Woodrow Wilson</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
<br>
&quot;Men by their constitution are naturally divided into two parties. 1. Those who fear and distrust the people, and wish to draw all powers from them into the hands of the higher classes.  2dly those who identify themselves with the people, have confidence in them, cherish and consider them as the most honest and safe, although not the most wise depository of the public interests.  <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>Thomas Jefferson, Letter to H. Lee, 1824</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
<br>
&quot;Guard with jealous attention the public liberty. Suspect every one who approaches that jewel. Unfortunately, nothing will preserve it but downright force. Whenever you give up that force, you are ruined.&quot;  <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>Patrick Henry, 1788</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
<br>
&quot;Gun control? It's the best thing you can do for crooks and gangsters.  I want you to have nothing.  If I'm a bad guy, I'm always gonna have a gun.   Safety locks?  You will pull the trigger with a lock on, and I'll pull the trigger.  We'll see who wins.&quot;  <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>Sammy &quot;the Bull&quot; Gravano (formerly of the Mafia) in a Vanity Fair interview.</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
