Fact is - if you think you need a gun, you shouldn't be allowed to have one. It presents the same spectacle as a child desparately clinging to its dirty, useless and ultimately harmful comfort blanket, howling pitifully as an adult tries to prise it from it's grasp. <br>
I note the lack of crime in the US - obviously due to criminals knowing that their victims will be armed...<br>
If you have a gun, its more likely that you, or a member of your family, will be shot with that weapon. It's highly unlikely that you'll have the opportunity to use it to defend yourself with it. It is likely that a gun used in the perpetration of a crime will not used by its registered owner. If you live in a society where guns are commonplace, you are more likely to be a victim of gun crime. <br>
More guns = bad thing. Less guns = good thing. It's time to grow up and leave the toys behind. <br>
I live in the UK, where you cannot have a gun legally without a good reason. Shootings are still headline news, as they are rare. Not commonplace, despite what is said. How many murders and shootings were commited in the US last week, that didn't even get a mention? It's become part of the background noise, and no-one notices anymore. <br>
